title: Change how to set profile for dynamic shape graphs in TensorRT EP
body:
When we run one yolov3 model from customer on TRT EP, an issue was found regarding how to set profile for dynamic shape (sub)graphs.
The model has more than one dynamic shape inputs. When the shape of some inputs changed, current way is to set/update profiles only for the changed inputs. However engine build failed on the yolov3 model. It turns out all dynamic shape inputs profiles need to be set even though just one of the inputs changes. This PR fixed the issue. Need to check with Nvidia if that's the right behavior for the profile API.

title: Handle missing initializers in allocation planner to fix crashes with DML provider
body:
This addresses crashes in certain models while creation sessions with the DML provider.

The problem is related to an optimization for memory size in which the DML graph partitioner transfers protobuf initializers out of the graph to manage itself.  The presence of the initializer though is needed for the allocation planner to call ProcessDef for that value and initialize reused_buffer_index".  With that field left initialized to zero, the planner thinks its decided to reuse the same buffer for that initializer and for another value at index zero, causing that buffer to be freed too many times / too early.

The fix is to initialize reused_buffer_index to -1 and detect this case, as well as make the allocation planner a bit more brittle.

title: Support OrtValue binding in Python to enable interesting IOBinding scenarios in Python
body:
This change is mostly about introducing an extensible Python binding for the `OrtValue` class that can be built-upon based on future requirements

With this binding support, new `IOBinding` scenarios are now possible. Some highlights are listed below:

- Allow users to allocate memory (and define contents of the memory) in CUDA (Limited to numeric tensors only for now)
  - Be self-sufficient and not rely on using custom allocators (for example, Torch) to do this


- Allow users to consume ORT allocated memory for outputs wrapped as OrtValues (mostly for tensor outputs with dynamic shapes)
  - This memory can be further used for other bindings if needed
  - Allow users to pass in such OrtValues to Run()

title: (abandoned) ORT DirectML EP for Iron release, ONNX 1.5 (part 2)
body:
# DRAFT ABANDONED

Recreated with correct branch history here: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5263

<s>**Description**: Includes collected bug fixes for this release.

**Motivation and Context**
- _Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?_
- ONNX zoo MaskRCNN and model fails to evaluate with DML
- Resample with empty tensors.
- Fix conflicting CMake linker flags with contradict those needed by the Windows inbox universal CRT. From Justin: "When building for release, linker optimization flags (/OPT:*) have been introduced globally for all executables and shared libs in the ORT CMake file. The WAI inbox toolchain doesn't permit this, since they may conflict or override settings already provided in the inbox UCRT msbuild properties. To work around this, I've added a CMake variable, onnxruntime_DISABLE_LINKER_OPT_FLAGS, which is undefined by default. The WAI root CMake file will define this to disable the conflicting flags, which is identical to how we handle spectre flags."
- Fix invalid WIN32 macro on Linux (scoped_env_vars.cc was using WIN32 instead of _WIN32 (the proper macro) to conditionally compile platform-specific code; this resulted in missing definitions for Linux functions, setenv and getenv).
- Avoid making copy initializer data which slows session creation down 30%.
</s>

title: Downgrade GCC
body:
**Description**: 

In 1.4 release, we used to have three different kind of build environment: 
1. Ubuntu for most of the CI pipelines
2. manylinux(which is based on CentOS) for python packaging pipeline.
3. CentOS6, which is for all the other packaging pipelines other than python.

The second one relies on Red Hat devtoolset, which gives us a much newer compiler version.

Recently, I tried to unify the docker images that were used in our packaging pipelines. I thought I can just use the manylinux one for all the cases. But unfortunately it's not true. The GCC in the manylinux docker image pulls in new openmp symbols, which are not available on Ubuntu 16.04. So, as long as our official builds still depend on openmp, we'll have to use the stock GCC version(4.8.5) instead. 

So this PR is to bring the third image back.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Linker opt flags - fix conflicting CMake linker flags which contradict those needed by the Windows inbox universal CRT
body:
**Description**: Fix conflicting CMake linker flags with contradict those needed by the Windows inbox universal CRT. From @jstoecker:
"When building for release, linker optimization flags (/OPT:*) have been introduced globally for all executables and shared libs in the ORT CMake file. The WAI inbox toolchain doesn't permit this, since they may conflict or override settings already provided in the inbox UCRT msbuild properties. I've added a CMake variable, onnxruntime_DISABLE_LINKER_OPT_FLAGS, which is undefined by default. The WAI root CMake file will define this to disable the conflicting flags, which is identical to how we handle spectre flags."

**Motivation and Context**
_Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?_
- Inbox DLLs need to link against the Universal CRT for security reasons, compliant with requirements for all inbox Windows components.

(note, not needed for ORT 1.5 release)

title: Transpose kernel fix for illegal memory access error
body:
**Description**: when copying input to tile, we need the additional check to see if input element index is beyond range. 

**Motivation and Context**
- In Mainz model input with dynamic shape, we often have shape not aligned with tile dim, .e.g. {1,462,16,64}. With perm {0,2,3,1}, it gets translated to {462, 1024} as MxN. Due to the uncommon shape, the math to calculate tile elem may go beyond input data range. Thus we need the similar check that we've already done for copying tile to output.

TODO - refactor the code and utilize the implementation in Transpose3DKernel for all these cases.
The code here is similar to this function. https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/16d35266ab9e060c5866a0cb629e37b50015130e/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/tensor/transpose_impl.cu#L13

The kernel Transpose3DKernel using block size 16x16 is better than the one using block size 32x8 which is used in the example https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/efficient-matrix-transpose-cuda-cc/

title: Add additional test cases to check for leaks in thread pool creation / destruction
body:
Add additional test cases such as ThreadPoolTest.TestPoolCreation_10Iter to create and destroy thread pools to watch for any memory leaks.  Running under Valgrind, these tests should show all of the data allocated being deallocated again.  

**Motivation and Context**
Two recent issues https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5176 and https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5292 indicated memory leaks.  The test cases help identify whether or not any of the data structures used in the thread pool are being leaked.  Currently, on WSL, the only data not being de-allocated in these tests are a small number of nsync waiter objects.  This behavior is as expected (the waiter objects should be held on a free list in the nsync library).

- Changed save/load flatfuffers code to only save/load when the string field actual exist
- Benefits, 
-- Can round trip valueinfo, 
-- Make test comparing valueinfo simpler.
-- Reduce the size of ort format file

title: Move Memcopy to and from host to default stream.
body:
Temporarily move memcopy to default stream to reduce a chance for memory space being accessed before async memcopy is complete.

Additional explanation by @KeDengMS :
"
GPU op 1 (in compute stream): uses tensor A as input, and then A is released to BFCArena with no reuse
GPU copy 2 (in copy stream): allocate a buffer for the copy output, and put fence on the buffer

From CPU threads point of view, these operations are sequential, but when compute stream and copy stream runs concurrently in GPU, theres a chance that the copy output of op2 happens at the same time when op1 is running in compute stream.
One solution is to make all copy and compute to be in the same GPU stream, so the CPU execution order and GPU execution order matches. 
"

title: Permit higher performance from Python FE by outputting all_finite on CPU and toggling GeluApproximation
body:
Enable higher performance from Python FE:
- Request 'all_finite' output tensor is bound to CPU
- Propagate GeluApproximation via option __internal_use.enable_gelu_approximation_.
(It's a holding place. Something like _graph_optimizations.enable_gelu_approximation_ would be more appropriate.)

**Motivation and Context**
The  'all_finite' tensor is bound to GPU by Python FE despite being output to CPU by IsAllFinite kernel. This causes the Python FE to block the CPU until the session is complete. It also causes needless CPU => GPU => CPU transfers. Also provide a means to propagate GeluApproximation to C++ backend.

As suggested, split into two PRs:
- https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5372
- https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5371

- This could be temporary, can setup a CI pipeline to report multiple minimal build size for different platform if we have such requirement in the future
